{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621676"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.71,0.06,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67229"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5048"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"9854"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22360"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67229"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset palpitations. Her heart rate is 180 beats per minute. The electrocardiogram shows a narrow complex tachycardia. A rapid intravenous bolus of adenosine is administered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacological properties of adenosine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sustained calcium channel blocker","Slow-onset beta receptor blocker","Rapid-acting atrioventricular node blocker","Long-acting sodium channel blocker","Long-acting adenosine receptor antagonist"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAdenosine is a \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid-acting atrioventricular node blocker\u003C/strong\u003E that works by activating adenosine A1 receptors, which increases potassium conductance and inhibits calcium currents in the atrioventricular node. This causes temporary heart block and can terminate re-entrant supraventricular tachycardias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdenosine is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Esustained calcium channel blocker\u003C/strong\u003E - its effect on calcium ion movement is indirect via a G-protein coupled receptor rather than acting at the calcium channel itself. This effect is also brief not sustained, with a half-life less than 10 seconds. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Eslow-onset beta receptor blocker\u003C/strong\u003E as it works through adenosine receptors rather than beta receptors and has a rapid onset of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdenosine does not primarily affect sodium channels and has a very short duration of action, therefore it is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Elong-acting sodium channel blocker\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe answer \u003Cstrong\u003Elong-acting adenosine receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; adenosine is an agonist rather than an antagonist and has an extremely short duration of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe extremely short half-life of adenosine (less than 10 seconds) is due to rapid cellular uptake and metabolism, which explains why it must be given as a rapid intravenous bolus. Common side effects include transient chest pain, flushing, and dyspnoea due to its vasodilatory effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adenosine causes rapid termination of supraventricular tachycardia by blocking atrioventricular node conduction.","Adenosine has a very short half-life of less than 10 seconds due to rapid cellular uptake and metabolism.","Side effects of adenosine include transient chest pain, flushing, and dyspnoea due to its vasodilatory effects."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T09:10:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:11:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67229"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},